# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: audio-codec-aac
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] The basic profile of AAC (both MPEG-4 and MPEG-2) is called **AAC-LC** (*Low Complexity*).
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] It is widely supported in the industry and has been adopted as the default or standard audio format on products including Apple's iTunes Store, Nintendo's Wii, DSi and 3DS and Sony's PlayStation 3.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] AAC has been further extended into HE-AAC (*High Efficiency*, or AAC+), which improves efficiency over AAC-LC.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Another variant is AAC-LD (*Low Delay*).
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] AAC supports inclusion of 48 full-bandwidth (up to 96 kHz) audio channels in one stream plus 16 low frequency effects (LFE, limited to 120 Hz) channels, up to 16 "coupling" or dialog channels, and up to 16 data streams.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] The quality for stereo is satisfactory to modest requirements at 96 kbit/s in joint stereo mode; however, hi-fi transparency demands data rates of at least 128 kbit/s (VBR).
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Tests of MPEG-4 audio have shown that AAC meets the requirements referred to as "transparent" for the ITU at 128 kbit/s for stereo, and 384 kbit/s for 5.1 audio.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] AAC uses only a modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT) algorithm, giving it higher compression efficiency than MP3, which uses a hybrid coding algorithm that is part MDCT and part FFT.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] The discrete cosine transform (DCT), a type of transform coding for lossy compression, was proposed by Nasir Ahmed in 1972, and developed by Ahmed with T.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Rao in 1973, publishing their results in 1974.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] This led to the development of the modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT), proposed by J.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Bradley in 1987, following earlier work by Princen and Bradley in 1986.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] The MP3 audio coding standard introduced in 1992 used a hybrid coding algorithm that is part MDCT and part FFT.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] AAC uses a purely MDCT algorithm, giving it higher compression efficiency than MP3.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Development further advanced when Lars Liljeryd introduced a method that radically shrank the amount of information needed to store the digitized form of a song or speech.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] AAC was developed with cooperation between AT&T Labs, Dolby, Fraunhofer IIS (who developed MP3) and Sony Corporation.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] AAC was officially declared an international standard by the Moving Picture Experts Group in April 1997.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] It is specified both as *Part 7 of the MPEG-2 standard*, and *Subpart 4 in Part 3 of the MPEG-4 standard*.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Further companies have contributed to development in later years including Bell Labs, LG Electronics, NEC, Nokia, Panasonic, ETRI, JVC Kenwood, Philips, Microsoft, and NTT.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] This part of MPEG-2 was a new part, since MPEG-2 already included *MPEG-2 Part 3*, formally known as *ISO/IEC 13818-3: MPEG-2 BC* (Backwards Compatible).
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Therefore, MPEG-2 Part 7 is also known as *MPEG-2 NBC* (Non-Backward Compatible), because it is not compatible with the MPEG-1 audio formats (MP1, MP2 and MP3).
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] MPEG-2 Part 7 defined three profiles: *Low-Complexity* profile (AAC-LC / LC-AAC), *Main* profile (AAC Main) and *Scalable Sampling Rate* profile (AAC-SSR).
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] The Main profile adds a set of recursive predictors that are calculated on each tap of the filterbank.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] The SSR uses a 4-band PQMF filterbank, with four shorter filterbanks following, in order to allow for scalable sampling rates.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] In 1999, MPEG-2 Part 7 was updated and included in the MPEG-4 family of standards and became known as *MPEG-4 Part 3*, *MPEG-4 Audio* or *ISO/IEC 14496-3:1999*.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] This update included several improvements.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] One of these improvements was the addition of *Audio Object Types* which are used to allow interoperability with a diverse range of other audio formats such as TwinVQ, CELP, HVXC, speech synthesis and MPEG-4 Structured Audio.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Another notable addition in this version of the AAC standard is *Perceptual Noise Substitution* (PNS).
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] In that regard, the AAC profiles (AAC-LC, AAC Main and AAC-SSR profiles) are combined with perceptual noise substitution and are defined in the MPEG-4 audio standard as Audio Object Types.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] MPEG-4 Audio Object Types are combined in four MPEG-4 Audio profiles: Main (which includes most of the MPEG-4 Audio Object Types), Scalable (AAC LC, AAC LTP, CELP, HVXC, TwinVQ, Wavetable Synthesis, TTSI), Speech (CELP, HVXC, TTSI) and Low Rate Synthesis (Wavetable Synthesis, TTSI).
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] The reference software for MPEG-4 Part 3 is specified in MPEG-4 Part 5 and the conformance bit-streams are specified in MPEG-4 Part 4.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] MPEG-4 Audio remains backward-compatible with MPEG-2 Part 7.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] It also defined four new audio profiles: High Quality Audio Profile, Low Delay Audio Profile, Natural Audio Profile and Mobile Audio Internetworking Profile.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] The HE-AAC Profile (AAC LC with SBR) and AAC Profile (AAC LC) were first standardized in ISO/IEC 14496-3:2001/Amd 1:2003.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] The HE-AAC v2 Profile (AAC LC with SBR and Parametric Stereo) was first specified in ISO/IEC 14496-3:2005/Amd 2:2006.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] The Parametric Stereo audio object type used in HE-AAC v2 was first defined in ISO/IEC 14496-3:2001/Amd 2:2004.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] The current version of the AAC standard is defined in ISO/IEC 14496-3:2019.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] AAC+ v2 is also standardized by ETSI (European Telecommunications Standards Institute) as TS 102005.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] The MPEG-4 Part 3 standard also contains other ways of compressing sound.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] These include lossless compression formats, synthetic audio and low bit-rate compression formats generally used for speech.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Advanced Audio Coding is designed to be the successor of the *MPEG-1 Audio Layer 3*, known as MP3 format, which was specified by ISO/IEC in 11172-3 (MPEG-1 Audio) and 13818-3 (MPEG-2 Audio).
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Overall, the AAC format allows developers more flexibility to design codecs than MP3 does, and corrects many of the design choices made in the original MPEG-1 audio specification.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] This increased flexibility often leads to more concurrent encoding strategies and, as a result, to more efficient compression.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] This is especially true at very low bit rates where the superior stereo coding, pure MDCT, and better transform window sizes leave MP3 unable to compete.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] While the MP3 format has near-universal hardware and software support, primarily because MP3 was the format of choice during the crucial first few years of widespread music file-sharing/distribution over the internet, AAC remained a strong contender due to some unwavering industry support.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Due to MP3's dominance, adoption of AAC was initially slow.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] The first commercialization was in 1997 when AT&T Labs (a co-owner of AAC patents) launched a digital music store with songs encoded in MPEG-2 AAC.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] HomeBoy for Windows was one of the earliest available AAC encoders and decoders.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Dolby Laboratories came in charge of AAC licensing in 2000.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] A new licensing model was launched by Dolby in 2002, while Nokia became a fifth co-licenser of the format.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Dolby itself also marketed its own coding format, Dolby AC-3.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Nokia started supporting AAC playback on devices as early as 2001, but it was the exclusive use of AAC by Apple Computer for their iTunes Store which accelerated attention to AAC.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Soon the format was also supported by Sony for their PlayStation Portable (albeit Sony continued promoting its proprietary ATRAC), and music-oriented cell phones from Sony Ericsson, beginning with the Sony Ericsson W800.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] The Windows Media Audio (WMA) format, from Microsoft, was considered to be AAC's main competitor.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] By 2017, AAC was considered to have become a *de facto* industry standard for lossy audio.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] AAC is a wideband audio coding algorithm that exploits two primary coding strategies to dramatically reduce the amount of data needed to represent high-quality digital audio: signal components that are perceptually irrelevant are discarded, and redundancies in the coded audio signal are eliminated.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] The encoding process begins by converting the signal from the time domain to the frequency domain using forward modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT), accomplished via filter banks that take an appropriate number of time samples and convert them to frequency samples.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] The frequency-domain signal is then quantized based on a psychoacoustic model and encoded.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Internal error correction codes are subsequently added before the signal is stored or transmitted.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] To prevent corrupt samples, a modern implementation of the Luhn mod N algorithm is applied to each frame.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] The MPEG-4 audio standard does not define a single or small set of highly efficient compression schemes but rather a complex toolbox to perform a wide range of operations from low bit rate speech coding to high-quality audio coding and music synthesis.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] AAC encoders can switch dynamically between a single MDCT block of length 1024 points or 8 blocks of 128 points (or between 960 points and 120 points, respectively).
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] AAC takes a modular approach to encoding.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Depending on the complexity of the bitstream to be encoded, the desired performance and the acceptable output, implementers may create profiles to define which of a specific set of tools they want to use for a particular application.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] The MPEG-4 Part 3 standard (MPEG-4 Audio) defined various new compression tools (a.k.a.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Audio Object Types) and their usage in brand new profiles.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] AAC is not used in some of the MPEG-4 Audio profiles.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] The MPEG-2 Part 7 AAC LC profile, AAC Main profile and AAC SSR profile are combined with Perceptual Noise Substitution and defined in the MPEG-4 Audio standard as Audio Object Types (under the name AAC LC, AAC Main and AAC SSR).
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] These are combined with other Object Types in MPEG-4 Audio profiles.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] One of many improvements in MPEG-4 Audio is an Object Type called Long Term Prediction (LTP), which is an improvement of the Main profile using a forward predictor with lower computational complexity.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Applying error protection enables error correction up to a certain extent.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Error correcting codes are usually applied equally to the whole payload.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] However, since different parts of an AAC payload show different sensitivity to transmission errors, this would not be a very efficient approach.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] The AAC payload can be subdivided into parts with different error sensitivities.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Error Resilience (ER) techniques can be used to make the coding scheme itself more robust against errors.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] They are closely derived from the MPEG-2 Advanced Audio Coding (AAC) format.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] AAC-ELD is recommended by GSMA as super-wideband voice codec in the IMS Profile for High Definition Video Conference (HDVC) Service.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] No licenses or payments are required for a user to stream or distribute audio in AAC format.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] This reason alone might have made AAC a more attractive format to distribute audio than its predecessor MP3, particularly for streaming audio (such as Internet radio) depending on the use case.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] However, a patent license is required for all manufacturers or developers of AAC "end-user" codecs.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] The terms (as disclosed to SEC) use per-unit pricing.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] In the case of software, each computer running the software is to be considered a separate "unit".
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] It used to be common for free and open source software implementations such as FFmpeg and FAAC to only be distributed in source code form so as to not "otherwise supply" an AAC codec.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] However, FFmpeg has since become more lenient on patent matters: the "gyan.dev" builds recommended by the official site now contain its AAC codec, with the FFmpeg legal page stating that patent law conformance is the user's responsibility.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] The AAC patent holders include Bell Labs, Dolby, ETRI, Fraunhofer, JVC Kenwood, LG Electronics, Microsoft, NEC, NTT (and its subsidiary NTT Docomo), Panasonic, Philips and Sony.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Based on the list of patents from the SEC terms, the last baseline AAC patent expires in 2028, and the last patent for all AAC extensions mentioned expires in 2031.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] In addition to the MP4, 3GP and other container formats based on ISO base media file format for file storage, AAC audio data was first packaged in a file for the MPEG-2 standard using Audio Data Interchange Format (ADIF), consisting of a single header followed by the raw AAC audio data blocks.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] However, if the data is to be streamed within an MPEG-2 transport stream, a self-synchronizing format called an **Audio Data Transport Stream** (**ADTS**) is used, consisting of a series of frames, each frame having a header followed by the AAC audio data.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] This file and streaming-based format are defined in MPEG-2 Part 7, but are only considered informative by MPEG-4, so an MPEG-4 decoder does not need to support either format.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] These containers, as well as a raw AAC stream, may bear the .aac file extension.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] MPEG-4 Part 3 also defines its own self-synchronizing format called a Low Overhead Audio Stream (LOAS) that encapsulates not only AAC, but any MPEG-4 audio compression scheme such as TwinVQ and ALS.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] This format is what was defined for use in DVB transport streams when encoders use either SBR or parametric stereo AAC extensions.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] However, it is restricted to only a single non-multiplexed AAC stream.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] This format is also referred to as a Low Overhead Audio Transport Multiplex (LATM), which is just an interleaved multiple stream version of a LOAS.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Apple's AAC encoder was first part of the QuickTime media framework but is now part of Audio Toolbox.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] FAAC and FAAD2 stand for Freeware Advanced Audio Coder and Decoder 2 respectively.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] FAAC supports audio object types LC, Main and LTP.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] FAAD2 supports audio object types LC, Main, LTP, SBR and PS.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Although FAAD2 is free software, FAAC is not free software.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] A Fraunhofer-authored open-source encoder/decoder included in Android has been ported to other platforms.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] FFmpeg's native AAC encoder does not support HE-AAC and HE-AACv2, but GPL 2.0+ of ffmpeg is not compatible with FDK AAC, hence ffmpeg with libfdk-aac is not redistributable.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] The QAAC encoder that is using Apple's Core Media Audio is still higher quality than FDK.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] The native AAC encoder created in FFmpeg's libavcodec, and forked with Libav, was considered experimental and poor.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] A significant amount of work was done for the 3.0 release of FFmpeg (February 2016) to make its version usable and competitive with the rest of the AAC encoders.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Libav has not merged this work and continues to use the older version of the AAC encoder.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] These encoders are LGPL-licensed open-source and can be built for any platform that the FFmpeg or Libav frameworks can be built.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Both FFmpeg and Libav can use the Fraunhofer FDK AAC library via libfdk-aac, and while the FFmpeg native encoder has become stable and good enough for common use, FDK is still considered the highest quality encoder available for use with FFmpeg.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Libav also recommends using FDK AAC if it is available.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] FFmpeg 4.4 and above can also use the Apple audiotoolbox encoder.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Although the native AAC encoder only produces AAC-LC, ffmpeg's native decoder is able to deal with a wide range of input formats.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] In May 2006, Nero AG released an AAC encoding tool free of charge, *Nero Digital Audio* (the AAC codec portion has become Nero AAC Codec), which is capable of encoding LC-AAC, HE-AAC and HE-AAC v2 streams.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] The tool is a command-line interface tool only.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] A separate utility is also included to decode to PCM WAV.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Various tools including the foobar2000 audio player and MediaCoder can provide a GUI for this encoder.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Almost all current computer media players include built-in decoders for AAC, or can utilize a library to decode it.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] On Microsoft Windows, DirectShow can be used this way with the corresponding filters to enable AAC playback in any DirectShow based player.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Mac OS X supports AAC via the QuickTime libraries.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Adobe Flash Player, since version 9 update 3, can also play back AAC streams.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Since Flash Player is also a browser plugin, it can play AAC files through a browser as well.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] The Rockbox open source firmware (available for multiple portable players) also offers support for AAC to varying degrees, depending on the model of player and the AAC profile.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Optional iPod support (playback of unprotected AAC files) for the Xbox 360 is available as a free download from Xbox Live.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Some of these players (e.g., foobar2000, Winamp, and VLC) also support the decoding of ADTS (Audio Data Transport Stream) using the SHOUTcast protocol.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Plug-ins for Winamp and foobar2000 enable the creation of such streams.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] In December 2003, Japan started broadcasting terrestrial DTV ISDB-T standard that implements MPEG-2 video and MPEG-2 AAC audio.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] In April 2006 Japan started broadcasting the ISDB-T mobile sub-program, called 1seg, that was the first implementation of video H.264/AVC with audio HE-AAC in Terrestrial HDTV broadcasting service on the planet.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] In December 2007, Brazil started broadcasting terrestrial DTV standard called International ISDB-Tb that implements video coding H.264/AVC with audio AAC-LC on main program (single or multi) and video H.264/AVC with audio HE-AACv2 in the 1seg mobile sub-program.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] The ETSI, the standards governing body for the DVB suite, supports AAC, HE-AAC and HE-AAC v2 audio coding in DVB applications since at least 2004.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] DVB broadcasts which use the H.264 compression for video normally use HE-AAC for audio.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] In April 2003, Apple brought mainstream attention to AAC by announcing that its iTunes and iPod products would support songs in MPEG-4 AAC format (via a firmware update for older iPods).
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Customers could download music in a closed-source digital rights management (DRM)-restricted form of 128 kbit/s AAC (see FairPlay) via the iTunes Store or create files without DRM from their own CDs using iTunes.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] In later years, Apple began offering music videos and movies, which also use AAC for audio encoding.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] On May 29, 2007, Apple began selling songs and music videos from participating record labels at higher bitrate (256 kbit/s cVBR) and free of DRM, a format dubbed "iTunes Plus" .
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] These files mostly adhere to the AAC standard and are playable on many non-Apple products but they do include custom iTunes information such as album artwork and a purchase receipt, so as to identify the customer in case the file is leaked out onto peer-to-peer networks.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] It is possible, however, to remove these custom tags to restore interoperability with players that conform strictly to the AAC specification.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] As of January 6, 2009, nearly all music on the USA regioned iTunes Store became DRM-free, with the remainder becoming DRM-free by the end of March 2009.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] iTunes offers a "Variable Bit Rate" encoding option which encodes AAC tracks in the Constrained Variable Bitrate scheme (a less strict variant of ABR encoding); the underlying QuickTime API does offer a true VBR encoding profile however.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] As of September 2009, Apple has added support for HE-AAC (which is fully part of the MP4 standard) only for radio streams, not file playback, and iTunes still lacks support for true VBR encoding.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] For a number of years, many mobile phones from manufacturers such as Nokia, Motorola, Samsung, Sony Ericsson, BenQ-Siemens and Philips have supported AAC playback.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] The first such phone was the Nokia 5510 released in 2002 which also plays MP3s.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] However, this phone was a commercial failure and such phones with integrated music players did not gain mainstream popularity until 2005 when the trend of having AAC as well as MP3 support continued.
[src:audio-codec-aac/advanced-audio-coding] Most new smartphones and music-themed phones support playback of these formats.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] In telecommunications and computing, **bit rate** (**bitrate** or as a variable *R*) is the number of bits that are conveyed or processed per unit of time.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] The bit rate is expressed as **bits per second** (symbol: **bit/s**), often with an SI prefix such as kilo (1 kbit/s = 1,000 bit/s), mega (1 Mbit/s = 1,000 kbit/s), giga (1 Gbit/s = 1,000 Mbit/s) or tera (1 Tbit/s = 1,000 Gbit/s).
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] The non-standard abbreviation **bps** is often used: 1 Mbps is 1 Mbit/s, that is, one million bits per second.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] The bit rate is different from the **transfer rate**, measured in transfers per second, when the channel is parallel and thus transfers multiple bits per transfer.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] In most computing and digital communication environments, one **byte per second** (symbol: **B/s**) corresponds to 8 bit/s (1 byte = 8 bits).
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] However if stop bits, start bits, and parity bits need to be factored in, a higher number of bits per second will be required to achieve a throughput of the same number of bytes.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] The binary prefixes defined by International Standard IEC 80000-13 are sometimes used: e.g., 1 KiB/s = 1024 B/s = 8192 bit/s, and 1 MiB/s = 1024 KiB/s.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] The gross bit rate is related to the symbol rate or modulation rate, which is expressed in baud or symbols per second.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] More specifically, a line code (or baseband transmission scheme) representing the data using pulse-amplitude modulation with $2^{N}$ different voltage levels, can transfer N bits per pulse.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] A digital modulation method (or passband transmission scheme) using $2^{N}$ different symbols, for example $2^{N}$ amplitudes, phases or frequencies, can transfer N bits per symbol.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] In practice this upper bound can only be approached for line coding schemes and for so-called vestigial sideband digital modulation.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] where *n* is the number of parallel channels, *Mi* is the number of symbols or levels of the modulation in the *i*th channel, and *Ti* is the symbol duration time, expressed in seconds, for the *i*th channel.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] Error-correcting codes are common especially in wireless communication systems, broadband modem standards and modern copper-based high-speed LANs.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] The physical layer net bitrate is the datarate measured at a reference point in the interface between the data link layer and physical layer, and may consequently include data link and higher layer overhead.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] In modems and wireless systems, link adaptation (automatic adaptation of the data rate and the modulation and/or error coding scheme to the signal quality) is often applied.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] In that context, the term **peak bitrate** denotes the net bitrate of the fastest and least robust transmission mode, used for example when the distance is very short between sender and transmitter.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] Some operating systems and network equipment may detect the "**connection speed**" (informal language) of a network access technology or communication device, implying the current net bit rate.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] The term **line rate** in some textbooks is defined as gross bit rate, in others as net bit rate.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] The relationship between the gross bit rate and net bit rate is affected by the FEC code rate according to the following.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] The connection speed of a technology that involves forward error correction typically refers to the physical layer *net bit rate* in accordance with the above definition.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] For example, the net bitrate (and thus the "connection speed") of an IEEE 802.11a wireless network is the net bit rate of between 6 and 54 Mbit/s, while the gross bit rate is between 12 and 72 Mbit/s inclusive of error-correcting codes.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] The net bit rate of ISDN2 Basic Rate Interface (2 B-channels + 1 D-channel) of 64+64+16 = 144 kbit/s also refers to the payload data rates, while the D channel signalling rate is 16 kbit/s.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] The net bit rate of the Ethernet 100BASE-TX physical layer standard is 100 Mbit/s, while the gross bitrate is 125 Mbit/s, due to the 4B5B (four bit over five bit) encoding.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] In this case, the gross bit rate is equal to the symbol rate or pulse rate of 125 megabaud, due to the NRZI line code.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] In communications technologies without forward error correction and other physical layer protocol overhead, there is no distinction between gross bit rate and physical layer net bit rate.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] For example, the net as well as gross bit rate of Ethernet 10BASE-T is 10 Mbit/s.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] Due to the Manchester line code, each bit is represented by two pulses, resulting in a pulse rate of 20 megabaud.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] The "connection speed" of a V.92 voiceband modem typically refers to the gross bit rate, since there is no additional error-correction code.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] It can be up to 56,000 bit/s downstream and 48,000 bit/s upstream.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] A lower bit rate may be chosen during the connection establishment phase due to adaptive modulation – slower but more robust modulation schemes are chosen in case of poor signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] Due to data compression, the actual data transmission rate or throughput (see below) may be higher.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] The channel capacity, also known as the Shannon capacity, is a theoretical upper bound for the maximum net bitrate, exclusive of forward error correction coding, that is possible without bit errors for a certain physical analog node-to-node communication link.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] The channel capacity is proportional to the analog bandwidth in hertz.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] This proportionality is called Hartley's law.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] Consequently, the net bit rate is sometimes called digital bandwidth capacity in bit/s.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] The term *throughput*, essentially the same thing as **digital bandwidth consumption**, denotes the achieved average useful bit rate in a computer network over a logical or physical communication link or through a network node, typically measured at a reference point above the data link layer.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] This implies that the throughput often excludes data link layer protocol overhead.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] The throughput is affected by the traffic load from the data source in question, as well as from other sources sharing the same network resources.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] As an example, the goodput or data transfer rate of a V.92 voiceband modem is affected by the modem physical layer and data link layer protocols.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] It is sometimes higher than the physical layer data rate due to V.44 data compression, and sometimes lower due to bit-errors and automatic repeat request retransmissions.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] In digital multimedia, bit rate represents the amount of information, or detail, that is stored per unit of time of a recording.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] Generally, choices are made about the above factors in order to achieve the desired trade-off between minimizing the bitrate and maximizing the quality of the material when it is played.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] If lossy data compression is used on audio or visual data, differences from the original signal will be introduced; if the compression is substantial, or lossy data is decompressed and recompressed, this may become noticeable in the form of compression artifacts.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] Whether these affect the perceived quality, and if so how much, depends on the compression scheme, encoder power, the characteristics of the input data, the listener's perceptions, the listener's familiarity with artifacts, and the listening or viewing environment.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] The encoding bit rate of a multimedia file is its size in bytes divided by the playback time of the recording (in seconds), multiplied by eight.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] For real-time streaming multimedia, the encoding bit rate is the goodput that is required to avoid playback interruption.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] The term average bitrate is used in case of variable bitrate multimedia source coding schemes.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] In this context, the *peak bit rate* is the maximum number of bits required for any short-term block of compressed data.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] A theoretical lower bound for the encoding bit rate for lossless data compression is the source information rate, also known as the *entropy rate*.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] The bitrates in this section are approximately the *minimum* that the *average* listener in a typical listening or viewing environment, when using the best available compression, would perceive as not significantly worse than the reference standard.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] Compact Disc Digital Audio (CD-DA) uses 44,100 samples per second, each with a bit depth of 16, a format sometimes abbreviated like "16bit / 44.1kHz".
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] CD-DA is also stereo, using a left and right channel, so the amount of audio data per second is double that of mono, where only a single channel is used.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] where **MiB** is mebibytes with binary prefix Mi, meaning 220 = 1,048,576.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] The MP3 audio format provides lossy data compression.
[src:audio-codec-aac/bit-rate] The Advanced Audio Coding (AAC) audio format provides lossy data compression or lossless data compression.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] This overlapping, in addition to the energy-compaction qualities of the DCT, makes the MDCT especially attractive for signal compression applications, since it helps to avoid artifacts stemming from the block boundaries.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] As a result of these advantages, the MDCT is the most widely used lossy compression technique in audio data compression.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] The discrete cosine transform (DCT) was first proposed by Nasir Ahmed in 1972, and demonstrated by Ahmed with T.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Bradley at the University of Surrey in 1987, following earlier work by Princen and Bradley (1986) to develop the MDCT's underlying principle of **time-domain aliasing cancellation** (TDAC), described below.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] In MP3, the MDCT is not applied to the audio signal directly, but rather to the output of a 32-band polyphase quadrature filter (PQF) bank.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] The output of this MDCT is postprocessed by an alias reduction formula to reduce the typical aliasing of the PQF filter bank.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Such a combination of a filter bank with an MDCT is called a *hybrid* filter bank or a *subband* MDCT.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] AAC, on the other hand, normally uses a pure MDCT; only the (rarely used) MPEG-4 AAC-SSR variant (by Sony) uses a four-band PQF bank followed by an MDCT.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Similar to MP3, ATRAC uses stacked quadrature mirror filters (QMF) followed by an MDCT.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] As a lapped transform, the MDCT is somewhat unusual compared to other Fourier-related transforms in that it has half as many outputs as inputs (instead of the same number).
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] In particular, it is a linear function $F\colon \mathbf {R} ^{2N}\to \mathbf {R} ^{N}$ (where **R** denotes the set of real numbers).
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] The normalization coefficient in front of this transform, here unity, is an arbitrary convention and differs between treatments.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Only the product of the normalizations of the MDCT and the IMDCT, below, is constrained.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] The inverse MDCT is known as the **IMDCT**.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Because there are different numbers of inputs and outputs, at first glance it might seem that the MDCT should not be invertible.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] However, perfect invertibility is achieved by *adding* the overlapped IMDCTs of subsequent overlapping blocks, causing the errors to *cancel* and the original data to be retrieved; this technique is known as *time-domain aliasing cancellation* (**TDAC**).
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Like for the DCT-IV, an orthogonal transform, the inverse has the same form as the forward transform.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] In the case of a windowed MDCT with the usual window normalization (see below), the normalization coefficient in front of the IMDCT should be multiplied by 2 (i.e., becoming 2/*N*).
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Although the direct application of the MDCT formula would require O(*N*2) operations, it is possible to compute the same thing with only O(*N* log *N*) complexity by recursively factorizing the computation, as in the fast Fourier transform (FFT).
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] One can also compute MDCTs via other transforms, typically a DFT (FFT) or a DCT, combined with O(*N*) pre- and post-processing steps.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Also, as described below, any algorithm for the DCT-IV immediately provides a method to compute the MDCT and IMDCT of even size.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] AC-3 uses a Kaiser–Bessel derived (KBD) window, and MPEG-4 AAC can also use a KBD window.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Note that windows applied to the MDCT are different from windows used for some other types of signal analysis, since they must fulfill the Princen–Bradley condition.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] One of the reasons for this difference is that MDCT windows are applied twice, for both the MDCT (analysis) and the IMDCT (synthesis).
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] As can be seen by inspection of the definitions, for *even* *N* the MDCT is essentially equivalent to a DCT-IV, where the input is shifted by *N*/2 and two *N*-blocks of data are transformed at once.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] By examining this equivalence more carefully, important properties like TDAC can be easily derived.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Thus, if its inputs are an array *x* of length *N*, we can imagine extending this array to (*x*, −*x**R*, −*x*, *x**R*, ...) and so on, where *x**R* denotes *x* in reverse order.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Consider an MDCT with 2*N* inputs and *N* outputs, where we divide the inputs into four blocks (*a*, *b*, *c*, *d*) each of size *N*/2.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] If we shift these to the right by *N*/2 (from the +*N*/2 term in the MDCT definition), then (*b*, *c*, *d*) extend past the end of the *N* DCT-IV inputs, so we must "fold" them back according to the boundary conditions described above.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] In this way, any algorithm to compute the DCT-IV can be trivially applied to the MDCT.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Similarly, the IMDCT formula above is precisely 1/2 of the DCT-IV (which is its own inverse), where the output is extended (via the boundary conditions) to a length 2*N* and shifted back to the left by *N*/2.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] The inverse DCT-IV would simply give back the inputs (−*c**R* − *d*, *a* − *b**R*) from above.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Half of the IMDCT outputs are thus redundant, as *b* − *a**R* = −(*a* − *b**R*)*R*, and likewise for the last two terms.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Suppose that one computes the MDCT of the subsequent, 50% overlapped, 2*N* block (*B*, *C*).
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] The IMDCT will then yield, analogous to the above: (*B* − *B**R*, *C* + *C**R*)/2.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] When this is added with the previous IMDCT result in the overlapping half, the reversed terms cancel and one obtains simply *B*, recovering the original data.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] The origin of the term "time-domain aliasing cancellation" is now clear.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] The combinations *c* − *d**R* and so on have precisely the right signs for the combinations to cancel when they are added.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] For *odd* *N* (which are rarely used in practice), *N*/2 is not an integer, so the MDCT is not simply a shift permutation of a DCT-IV.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] In this case, the additional shift by half a sample means that the MDCT/IMDCT becomes equivalent to the DCT-III/II, and the analysis is analogous to the above.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] We have seen above that the MDCT of 2*N* inputs (*a*, *b*, *c*, *d*) is equivalent to a DCT-IV of the *N* inputs (−*c**R* − *d*, *a* − *b**R*).
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT-IV is designed for the case where the function at the right boundary is odd, and therefore the values near the right boundary are close to 0.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] If the input signal is smooth, this is the case: the rightmost components of *a* and *b**R* are consecutive in the input sequence (*a*, *b*, *c*, *d*), and therefore their difference is small.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Let us look at the middle of the interval: if we rewrite the above expression as (−*c**R* − *d*, *a* − *b**R*) = (−*d*, *a*) − (*b*, *c*)*R*, the second term, (*b*, *c*)*R*, gives a smooth transition in the middle.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] However, in the first term, (−*d*, *a*), there is a potential discontinuity where the right end of −*d* meets the left end of *a*.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] This is the reason for using a window function that reduces the components near the boundaries of the input sequence (*a*, *b*, *c*, *d*) towards 0.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Above, the TDAC property was proved for the ordinary MDCT, showing that adding IMDCTs of subsequent blocks in their overlapping half recovers the original data.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] The derivation of this inverse property for the windowed MDCT is only slightly more complicated.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Consider two overlapping consecutive sets of 2*N* inputs (*A*,*B*) and (*B*,*C*), for blocks *A*,*B*,*C* of size *N*.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Recall from above that when $(A,B)$ and $(B,C)$ are MDCTed, IMDCTed, and added in their overlapping half, we obtain $(B+B_{R})/2+(B-B_{R})/2=B$ , the original data.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Now we suppose that we multiply *both* the MDCT inputs *and* the IMDCT outputs by a window function of length 2*N*.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] As above, we assume a symmetric window function, which is therefore of the form $(W,W_{R})$ where *W* is a length-*N* vector and *R* denotes reversal as before.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Then the Princen-Bradley condition can be written as $W^{2}+W_{R}^{2}=(1,1,\ldots )$ , with the squares and additions performed elementwise.
[src:audio-codec-aac/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Therefore, instead of MDCTing $(A,B)$ , we now MDCT $(WA,W_{R}B)$ (with all multiplications performed elementwise).
[src:audio-codec-aac/perceptual-coding] Perceptual coding is based on models of human hearing and vision, such as those studied in psychoacoustics and psychovisual research.
[src:audio-codec-aac/perceptual-coding] By discarding or reducing components of a signal that fall below perceptual thresholds, it achieves significant reductions in bit rate while maintaining a subjectively acceptable quality.
[src:audio-codec-aac/perceptual-coding] The principles of perceptual coding were applied in analog communication systems long before the advent of digital media.
[src:audio-codec-aac/perceptual-coding] These analog systems demonstrated the effectiveness of tailoring transmission to the characteristics of human perception, laying the groundwork for digital perceptual coding methods.
[src:audio-codec-aac/perceptual-coding] Research in the 1970s and 1980s on psychoacoustics and psychovisual modeling provided the basis for digital perceptual coding.
[src:audio-codec-aac/perceptual-coding] In audio, this led to the late-1980s development of the MPEG audio formats (such as MP3), which achieved major reductions in bit rate by discarding inaudible sound components.
[src:audio-codec-aac/perceptual-coding] At the same time, the MPEG standards applied similar principles to video, using techniques such as chroma subsampling and motion-adaptive coding.
[src:audio-codec-aac/perceptual-coding] During the 1990s and 2000s, perceptual coding was embedded in widely used formats including AAC, MPEG-2 video, and H.264/AVC, supporting the rise of digital media distribution on CDs, DVDs, and early internet platforms.
[src:audio-codec-aac/perceptual-coding] More recent codecs, such as HEVC, AV1, and Opus, continue to refine perceptual models to balance compression efficiency with quality on modern networks and devices.
[src:audio-codec-aac/perceptual-coding] Perceptual coding draws directly on psychoacoustics (the study of auditory perception) and psychovisual research (the study of visual perception).
[src:audio-codec-aac/perceptual-coding] These disciplines provide the models that determine which parts of a signal can be safely removed without affecting perceived quality.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Hearing is not a purely mechanical phenomenon of wave propagation, but is also a sensory and perceptual event.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] When a person hears something, that something arrives at the ear as a mechanical sound wave traveling through the air, but within the ear it is transformed into neural action potentials.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] These nerve pulses then travel to the brain where they are perceived.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Hence, in many problems in acoustics, such as for audio processing, it is advantageous to take into account not just the mechanics of the environment, but also the fact that both the ear and the brain are involved in a person's listening experience.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] The inner ear, for example, does significant signal processing in converting sound waveforms into neural stimuli, this processing renders certain differences between waveforms imperceptible.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Data compression techniques, such as MP3, make use of this fact.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] In addition, the ear has a nonlinear response to sounds of different intensity levels; this nonlinear response is called loudness.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Telephone networks and audio noise reduction systems make use of this fact by nonlinearly compressing data samples before transmission and then expanding them for playback.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Another effect of the ear's nonlinear response is that sounds that are close in frequency produce phantom beat notes, or intermodulation distortion products.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] There are at least five features to identify effective psychoacoustic practices: Loudness (the measures of perceived volume), Roughness (sensory dissonance), Sharpness (spectral distribution), Tonalness (the ratio of tonal spectral peaks), and Spaciousness (to predict perceived Spaciousness).
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Another procedure for recognizing music genres or recommending music is to remove a wide range of objective features that are not entirely related to human perception.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] However, there are some low level features that aren't related to human/physical perception, but can improve the discovery of psychoacoustics.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] The first one, Root Mean Square (RMS), is another way how sound can be measured, specifically loudness.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] RMS is a significant process of measurement because it helps people monitor volume.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Spectral Rolloff helps guide the frequency to a balance.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Spectral Flatness is considered to outline how loud or quite a noise range.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Lastly, Inter Channel Cross Correlation estimates the relationship between how one ear perceived sound in relation to the other ear.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] The human ear can nominally hear sounds in the range 20 to 20000 Hz.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] The upper limit tends to decrease with age; most adults are unable to hear above 16000 Hz.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Under ideal laboratory conditions, the lowest frequency that has been identified as a musical tone is 12 Hz.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Tones between 4 and 16 Hz can be perceived via the body's sense of touch.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Human perception of audio signal time separation has been measured to be less than 10 μs.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] This does not mean that frequencies above 100 kHz (1/10 μs) are audible, but that time discrimination is not directly coupled with frequency range.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Frequency resolution of the ear is about 3.6 Hz within the octave of 1000–2000 Hz That is, changes in pitch larger than 3.6 Hz can be perceived in a clinical setting.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] However, even smaller pitch differences can be perceived through other means.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] For example, the interference of two pitches can often be heard as a repetitive variation in the volume of the tone.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] This amplitude modulation occurs with a frequency equal to the difference in frequencies of the two tones and is known as beating.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] The semitone scale used in Western musical notation is not a linear frequency scale but logarithmic.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] The intensity range of audible sounds is enormous.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Human eardrums are sensitive to variations in sound pressure and can detect pressure changes from as small as a few micropascals (μPa) to greater than 100 kPa.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] For this reason, sound pressure level is also measured logarithmically, with all pressures referenced to 20 μPa (or 1.97385×10−10 atm).
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] The lower limit of audibility is therefore defined as 0 dB, but the upper limit is not as clearly defined.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] The upper limit is more a question of the potential to cause noise-induced hearing loss.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] A more rigorous exploration of the lower limits of audibility determines that the minimum threshold at which a sound can be heard is frequency dependent.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] By measuring this minimum intensity for test tones of various frequencies, a frequency-dependent absolute threshold of hearing (ATH) curve may be derived.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Typically, the ear shows a peak of sensitivity (i.e., its lowest ATH) between 1–5 kHz, though the threshold changes with age, with older ears showing decreased sensitivity above 2 kHz.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] The ATH is the lowest of the equal-loudness contours.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Equal-loudness contours indicate the sound pressure level (dB SPL), over the range of audible frequencies that are perceived as being of equal loudness.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Equal-loudness contours were first measured by Fletcher and Munson at Bell Labs in 1933 using pure tones reproduced via headphones, and the data they collected are called Fletcher–Munson curves.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Because subjective loudness was difficult to measure, the Fletcher–Munson curves were averaged over many subjects.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Robinson and Dadson refined the process in 1956 to obtain a new set of equal-loudness curves for a frontal sound source measured in an anechoic chamber.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] The Robinson-Dadson curves were standardized as ISO 226 in 1986.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] In 2003, ISO 226 was revised using data collected from 12 international studies.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Sound localization is the process of determining the location of a sound source.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] The brain utilizes subtle differences in loudness, tone and timing between the two ears to allow us to localize sound sources.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Localization can be described in terms of three-dimensional position: the azimuth or horizontal angle, the zenith or vertical angle, and the distance (for static sounds) or velocity (for moving sounds).
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Humans, as most four-legged animals, are adept at detecting direction in the horizontal, but less so in the vertical directions due to the ears being placed symmetrically.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Some species of owls have their ears placed asymmetrically and can detect sound in all three planes, an adaptation to hunt small mammals in the dark.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Suppose a listener can hear a given acoustical signal under silent conditions.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] When a signal is playing while another sound is being played, the signal has to be stronger for the listener to hear it.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] The interfering signal is known as the *masker* and the impeded listening, *masking*.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] The masker does not need to have the frequency components of the original signal for masking to happen.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] A masked signal can be heard even though it is weaker than the masker.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Masking happens when a signal and a masker are played together—for instance, when one person whispers while another person shouts—and the listener doesn't hear the weaker signal as it has been masked by the louder masker.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Masking can also happen to a signal before a masker starts or after a masker stops.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] For example, a sudden loud clap sound can make sounds inaudible immediately preceding or following.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] The effect of backward masking is weaker than forward masking.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] The masking effect has been widely studied in psychoacoustical research and are exploited in lossy audio encoding, such as MP3.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] When presented with a harmonic series of frequencies in the relationship 2*f*, 3*f*, 4*f*, 5*f*, etc.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] (where *f* is a specific frequency), humans tend to perceive that the pitch is *f*.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] An audible example can be found on YouTube.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Psychoacoustics includes topics and studies that are relevant to music psychology and music therapy.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Theorists such as Benjamin Boretz consider some of the results of psychoacoustics to be meaningful only in a musical context.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Irv Teibel's *Environments series* LPs (1969–79) are an early example of commercially available sounds released expressly for enhancing psychological abilities.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Psychoacoustics has long enjoyed a symbiotic relationship with computer science.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Licklider and Bob Taylor both completed graduate-level work in psychoacoustics, while BBN Technologies originally specialized in consulting on acoustics issues before it began building the first packet-switched network.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Licklider wrote a paper entitled "A duplex theory of pitch perception".
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Psychoacoustics is applied within many fields of software development, where developers map proven and experimental mathematical patterns in digital signal processing.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Many audio compression codecs such as MP3 and Opus use a psychoacoustic model to increase compression ratios.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] The success of conventional audio systems for the reproduction of music in theatres and homes can be attributed to psychoacoustics and psychoacoustic considerations gave rise to novel audio systems, such as psychoacoustic sound field synthesis.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Furthermore, scientists have experimented with limited success in creating new acoustic weapons, which emit frequencies that may impair, harm, or kill.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Psychoacoustics are also leveraged in sonification to make multiple independent data dimensions audible and easily interpretable.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] This enables auditory guidance without the need for spatial audio and in sonification computer games and other applications, such as drone flying and image-guided surgery.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] It is also applied today within music, where musicians and artists continue to create new auditory experiences by masking unwanted frequencies of instruments, causing other frequencies to be enhanced.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Yet another application is in the design of small or lower-quality loudspeakers, which can use the phenomenon of missing fundamentals to give the effect of bass notes at lower frequencies than the loudspeakers are physically able to produce (see references).
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Automobile manufacturers engineer their engines and even doors to have a certain sound.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] The psychoacoustic model provides for high-quality lossy signal compression by describing which parts of a given digital audio signal can be removed or reproduced with reduced quality without significant loss in the perceived quality of the sound.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] This provides great benefit to the overall compression ratio, and psychoacoustic analysis routinely leads to compressed music files that are one-tenth to one-twelfth the size of high-quality masters, but with discernibly less proportional quality loss.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Such compression is a feature of nearly all modern lossy audio compression formats.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Some of these formats include Dolby Digital (AC-3), MP3, Opus, Ogg Vorbis, AAC, WMA, MPEG-1 Layer II (used for digital audio broadcasting in several countries), and ATRAC, the compression used in MiniDisc and some Walkman models.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Psychoacoustics is based heavily on human anatomy, especially the ear's limitations in perceiving sound as outlined previously.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] A compression algorithm can assign a lower priority to sounds outside the range of human hearing and reduce the precision of different frequencies according to the predicted masking level.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] By carefully shifting bits away from the unimportant components and toward the important ones, the algorithm ensures that the sounds a listener is most likely to perceive are most accurately represented.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Audio encoders analyse audio using a perceptual model (psychoacoustic model), in order to compute the required precision per frequency band or temporal section.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] Results of this computation are then used to adjust coding precision as a function of frequency and time through a set of coding tools that are dependent on the audio encoding format, as different formats support different coding tools.
[src:audio-codec-aac/psychoacoustics] In many encoders, a rate control algorithm ensures that the resulting bitrate of the coded audio is within defined limits.
